(2030, 1, '2016-02-13 06:23:55', '2016-02-13 06:23:55', 'The philosophy of proCFO is simple:\n\n<strong>Our mission is to streamline your financial services, creating and adding significant value to your business by using our reliable, accurate and affordable virtual CFO solutions so you can grow your business.\n\n</strong>proCFO aim to make high-level financial services accessible to small businesses, new businesses and start-ups.\n\nWe put customers first by communicating and working together to solve your accounting needs.\n\nAt proCFO we help our clients make sense of the rapidly changing digital landscape and are committed to building a roadmap for your business that will ensure it continues to be relevant and viable.', 'Philosophy', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'philosophy', '', '', '2016-02-13 06:23:55', '2016-02-13 06:23:55', '', 1797, 'http://www.procfo.com.au/?page_id=2030', 10, 'page', '', 0),
(2042, 1, '2016-02-13 06:31:52', '2016-02-13 06:31:52', '<strong>Case Study </strong>\n\nLast year proCFO met with a client whose internal bookkeeper had just informed them of a family tragedy, and told the client they needed to take immediate leave for 2 weeks.\n\nThis person had sole responsibility for accounts payable processing and the business could not afford to leave this function unattended.\n\nWithin 24 hours we had implemented a system that reduced accounts payable processing time by 12 hours per week, saving the business over $30,000 p.a.\n\nThe supplier invoices were scanned and put through a processing engine that would automatically capture the necessary information to enable upload into the client''s MYOB file from file data.\n\nThere was an initial learning curve regarding classification of certain suppliers, but once addressed it merely became a process of managing the exceptions.', 'Form Case Studies', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'form-stage', '', '', '2016-02-13 06:31:52', '2016-02-13 06:31:52', '', 101, 'http://www.procfo.com.au/?page_id=2042', 12, 'page', '', 0),
(2044, 1, '2016-02-13 06:32:09', '2016-02-13 06:32:09', '<strong>Case Study</strong>\n\nA manufacturing client had been steadily losing money for 2 years when they came to us. They supplied niche plumbing products to large stores like Bunnings and to independent plumbers.\n\nproCFO reviewed their pricing and found their gross profit margins had declined over recent years as they were offering the biggest discounts to the lowest volume purchaser (because they whinged the loudest and most frequently!).\n\nproCFO suggested establishing a tiered pricing structure, based on purchase volumes with a price increase thrown in. The client was very concerned about losing customers but after understanding the competition and other sources of supply, he agreed to try a price increase.\n\nThe initial price increase of 10% was met without a whisper from a single client!  They clearly knew he was too cheap but were never going to tell him that!\n\nOver the next 2 years we raised prices every 6 months roughly in step with raw material increases and returned the business to healthy profit.', 'Storm Case Studies', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'storm-stage', '', '', '2016-02-13 06:32:09', '2016-02-13 06:32:09', '', 101, 'http://www.procfo.com.au/?page_id=2044', 7, 'page', '', 0),
(2046, 1, '2016-02-13 06:32:23', '2016-02-13 06:32:23', '<strong>Case Study </strong>\n\nproCFO was working with an electrical contractor who had a team that were each allocated responsibility for their own van.\n\nThey had authority to purchase stock for their allocated jobs from the approved wholesaler, but during the <a href="http://www.procfo.com.au/our-packages/perform/#voice-perform">Voice of the Team</a> session it became apparent that there was no standard stock level in any of the vans, and in more than 60% of cases they would have to leave a job to get supplies.\n\nAdding to the problem, the accounts payable section had dozens of small invoices to process every week for all these sundry purchases.\n\nWe resolved this issue by negotiating a deal with the wholesaler to fully stock each van with a standard range of products on consignment.\n\nThe electrician then only had to go to the wholesaler every few days, to re-stock to the standard level and the accounts payable area received a single invoice each week for the value of the stock that had been replenished.', 'Perform Case Studies', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'perform-stage', '', '', '2016-02-13 06:32:23', '2016-02-13 06:32:23', '', 101, 'http://www.procfo.com.au/?page_id=2046', 6, 'page', '', 0),
(2048, 1, '2016-02-13 06:32:35', '2016-02-13 06:32:35', '<strong>Case Study </strong>\n\nOur client was a supplier of IT printing consumables.  We ran a <a href="http://www.procfo.com.au/our-packages/custom/#voice-custom">Voice of the Customer</a> with their key clients and learned that their main frustration with our client (and his competitors) was that they often ran out of stock of items.\n\nAfter analysis of their back order book, it transpired that 20% of all orders were dispatched with at least 1 item on back order.  There was an enormous cost to the business to deliver small quantities once stock arrived.\n\nThis business ran on very tight gross margins and customers were highly price sensitive.   The main issue was that the business owner had set a ''cap'' on the value of inventory and refused to carry more stock.\n\nThis resulted in high level of enquiry for price and availability of items, with lots of time and resources wasted as a result.\n\nWe suggested the client offer a ''guarantee of supply'' for his top 100 items (accounting for about 90% of sales revenue each month).  The client baulked, saying it would send him broke and his suppliers often let him down too!\n\nTo solve this problem, we approached the key supplier requesting they provide a guarantee of supply for the same 100 items - which they agreed to do.\n\nThis resulted in a win- win situation. Our client was able to crib a slight price increase from being able to guarantee supply, and if he has to honour his guarantee, the supplier is the one who needed to "cough up".', 'Custom Case Studies', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'custom-stage', '', '', '2016-02-13 06:32:35', '2016-02-13 06:32:35', '', 101, 'http://www.procfo.com.au/?page_id=2048', 5, 'page', '', 0),
